XCIII. In the country (?), autumn (?), 44 Bc. On Quintus, cf. Intr. 553 on Tiro, Intr. 57.

1. verberavi: in the figurative sense as in Plaut. M. G. 799.— fasciculus: a packet of letters. Cf. Att. 12. 53.

2. etiamsi . . . scribito tamen: cf. A tt. 4. 8 Β. 4 nbi nillil erit quod scribas, z'd ipsum scribite, and Plin. Ep. 1. 11. -— mi: for milzi. This form (found also in Ep. LXVII. 3) illustrates well the connection which often exists between ar- chaism and colloquialism. In

early Latin mi was in good use in all forms of literature; at the be- ginning of the classical period it had dropped out of use in formal literature, but had been retained in that literature which reproduced the doings and sayings of every- day life. This is the history of many forms and expressions3 cf. Intr. 70.
